Experiment 15

To implement the  use of the single public and private inheritance.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Aim:

To write a C++ program to implement single inheritance using public and private inheritance and observe how memberare inherited in each case.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Algorithm:

1. Start the program.
2. Create a base class with:
private members
protected members
public members
3. Create a derived class using:
public inheritance
private inheritance
4. Inside the derived class:
Try accessing base class members and observe which are accessible.
5. Create objects of the derived class.
6. Call functions to show:
What is accessible in public inheritance
What is accessible in private inheritance
7. Display the results.
8. End the program.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Source Code (C++):


#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Base {
private:
    int a;        // Not inherited
protected:
    int b;        // Inherited but not accessible directly in main
public:
    int c;        // Inherited and accessible based on mode

    Base() {
        a = 10;
        b = 20;
        c = 30;
    }

    void showBase() {
        cout << "Base class: a=" << a << " b=" << b << " c=" << c << endl;
    }
};

// ---------- Public Inheritance ----------
class DerivedPublic : public Base {
public:
    void show() {
        // a not accessible
        cout << "DerivedPublic accessing b = " << b << endl;
        cout << "DerivedPublic accessing c = " << c << endl;
    }
};

// ---------- Private Inheritance ----------
class DerivedPrivate : private Base {
public:
    void show() {
        // b and c become private in this class
        cout << "DerivedPrivate accessing b = " << b << endl;
        cout << "DerivedPrivate accessing c = " << c << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    DerivedPublic dp;
    DerivedPrivate dpr;

    cout << "----- Public Inheritance -----" << endl;
    dp.show();        // b & c accessible
    cout << "Accessing public member c from object = " << dp.c << endl;

    cout << "\n----- Private Inheritance -----" << endl;
    dpr.show();       // Allowed through function
    // dpr.c; // âŒ Not allowed (private)

    return 0;
}
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Output

----- Public Inheritance -----
DerivedPublic accessing b = 20
DerivedPublic accessing c = 30
Accessing public member c from object = 30

----- Private Inheritance -----
DerivedPrivate accessing b = 20
DerivedPrivate accessing c = 30
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Result

The program successfully demonstrates single inheritance in two modes:



public and protected members of Base â†’ become private in DerivedPrivate

Cannot be accessed from an object of the derived class.


Thus, the behavior of inheritance changes based on the mode used.


